JACQUES PEPIN: What dish
have I done the most?

00:44:37.760 --> 00:44:39.710
Probably soup.

00:44:39.710 --> 00:44:44.020
We always have soup at home
during the winter, too.

00:44:44.020 --> 00:44:46.920
Often, what my wife
calls French soup--

00:44:46.920 --> 00:44:48.890
open the refrigerator,
what's there

00:44:48.890 --> 00:44:51.700
from salad leftover, a
carrot, this, that too.

00:44:51.700 --> 00:44:55.459
In fact, I remember, the
first series that I did

00:44:55.459 --> 00:44:56.500
called "Today's Gourmet."

00:44:56.500 --> 00:44:59.540
It was in 1989, I
believe, at KQED.

00:44:59.540 --> 00:45:03.776
And Claudine, my daughter, at
that time was in college at BU.

00:45:03.776 --> 00:45:06.830
I teach at BU also
for 32 years now.

00:45:06.830 --> 00:45:11.110
So Claudine was at BU, and
she came to the show with me.

00:45:11.110 --> 00:45:14.030
And Peter Stein was the
producer at the time.

00:45:14.030 --> 00:45:15.010
And we finished.

00:45:15.010 --> 00:45:15.980
We went fast.

00:45:15.980 --> 00:45:17.970
He say, you have
three minutes left.

00:45:17.970 --> 00:45:19.570
What can you do?

00:45:19.570 --> 00:45:22.220
I say, well let's do
a soup, or whatever.

00:45:22.220 --> 00:45:24.130
So I went into the
refrigerator, pick up

00:45:24.130 --> 00:45:26.590
the wilted carrot, a
piece of [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:26.590 --> 00:45:29.120
I tell Claudine, what do you
have in your refrigerator

00:45:29.120 --> 00:45:30.220
at school?

00:45:30.220 --> 00:45:33.144
So she brought me
all that stuff.

00:45:33.144 --> 00:45:34.560
She said, well,
we throw that out.

00:45:34.560 --> 00:45:35.320
I said, uh-uh.

00:45:35.320 --> 00:45:37.930
So I did a soup or
whatever I did with her,

00:45:37.930 --> 00:45:41.280
and it was one of the segments
people loved the most.

00:45:41.280 --> 00:45:42.647
[INAUDIBLE]

00:45:42.647 --> 00:45:43.730
MARCIA GAGLIARDI: Love it.

00:45:43.730 --> 00:45:46.790
JACQUES PEPIN: Thank you.

00:45:46.790 --> 00:45:49.635
AUDIENCE: The relationships
with people around me

00:45:49.635 --> 00:45:51.760
have a profound
influence on my cooking.

00:45:51.760 --> 00:45:56.530
I tend to try to perfect dishes
that the people who I love

00:45:56.530 --> 00:45:57.490
love.

00:45:57.490 --> 00:46:00.330
And if I want to go home and
do something nice for my wife,

00:46:00.330 --> 00:46:03.120
I've got a bouquet of flowers
and a bag of buckwheat flour

00:46:03.120 --> 00:46:04.610
to make her blini.

00:46:04.610 --> 00:46:07.075
I'm curious if the
relationships you have

00:46:07.075 --> 00:46:09.340
have had a similar
influence on your cooking,

00:46:09.340 --> 00:46:11.090
and is there a particular
dish that you've

00:46:11.090 --> 00:46:13.710
tried to perfect to
make somebody happy?

00:46:13.710 --> 00:46:17.340
JACQUES PEPIN: Well, you always
cook for the people love,

00:46:17.340 --> 00:46:20.190
without any question-- for the
family, the most important.

00:46:20.190 --> 00:46:24.740
But after 48 years
of marriage, my wife

00:46:24.740 --> 00:46:28.800
may have asked my
advice years ago.

00:46:28.800 --> 00:46:31.674
Now, usually, when I go into
the kitchen, she's cooking.

00:46:31.674 --> 00:46:33.590
She don't tell me,
darling, what do you think?

00:46:33.590 --> 00:46:37.120
She tells me, don't
touch anything.

00:46:37.120 --> 00:46:40.960
So yes, being born in New
York from a Puerto Rican

00:46:40.960 --> 00:46:43.260
mother and a Cuban father.

00:46:43.260 --> 00:46:47.740
So there is some
Caribbean influence

00:46:47.740 --> 00:46:49.230
in it, too, and taste.

00:46:49.230 --> 00:46:53.980
And she loves Japanese cooking
as well as Vietnamese, too.

00:46:53.980 --> 00:46:56.900
So she cooks some of that, we
cook some of that together.

00:46:56.900 --> 00:46:59.110
But we do cook together.

00:46:59.110 --> 00:47:01.660
But after those
years, so many years,

00:47:01.660 --> 00:47:03.870
we don't even have
to talk too much.

00:47:03.870 --> 00:47:07.420
We have our area, which have
been pretty much divided

00:47:07.420 --> 00:47:08.344
throughout the years.

00:47:08.344 --> 00:47:09.760
MARCIA GAGLIARDI:
Like the closet.

00:47:13.489 --> 00:47:14.030
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:47:14.030 --> 00:47:14.946
It's great to be here.

00:47:14.946 --> 00:47:16.540
Thank you.

00:47:16.540 --> 00:47:20.130
I'm reading the book, "The Third
Plate" by Dan Barber right now,

00:47:20.130 --> 00:47:21.181
the future of our plate.

00:47:21.181 --> 00:47:23.180
And I was wondering what
you thought about that.

00:47:23.180 --> 00:47:27.770
What would be-- what does our
plate look like in the future?

00:47:27.770 --> 00:47:30.000
JACQUES PEPIN: I'm sorry,
I couldn't-- I'm old.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:31.850
AUDIENCE: So that's the
future of our plate.

00:47:31.850 --> 00:47:34.030
What does our plate look
like in our future--

00:47:34.030 --> 00:47:36.500
near future, far future.

00:47:36.500 --> 00:47:38.210
What does our plate look like?

00:47:38.210 --> 00:47:41.110
JACQUES PEPIN: What our food
will look like in general?

00:47:41.110 --> 00:47:44.840
What I hope that--
actually, there is hope.

00:47:44.840 --> 00:47:48.410
We are going back, it
seems to me, more the way

00:47:48.410 --> 00:47:50.320
we cooked many years ago.

00:47:50.320 --> 00:47:52.090
Maybe not the way.

00:47:52.090 --> 00:47:57.150
I talk about my mother--
my mother died a month

00:47:57.150 --> 00:47:58.370
and a half ago.

00:47:58.370 --> 00:48:00.770
She was 99 and 1/2, too.

00:48:00.770 --> 00:48:03.960
And I went to see her
in July this summer.

00:48:03.960 --> 00:48:05.640
I talk about my
mother and my father.

00:48:05.640 --> 00:48:07.530
I said, my mother was
an organic farmer.

00:48:07.530 --> 00:48:08.770
My father, too.

00:48:08.770 --> 00:48:12.060
Well, the word organic
did not exist anyway.

00:48:12.060 --> 00:48:14.380
But since chemical
fertilizer did not

00:48:14.380 --> 00:48:18.130
exist either and
fungicide, insecticide,

00:48:18.130 --> 00:48:21.260
pesticide did not exist
either, everyone was organic.

00:48:21.260 --> 00:48:23.180
That was the way it was.

00:48:23.180 --> 00:48:27.430
In addition to this, my mother
had a small restaurant there,

00:48:27.430 --> 00:48:30.580
which may sound
pretty romantic now,

00:48:30.580 --> 00:48:33.080
which we didn't think it
was romantic at the time.

00:48:33.080 --> 00:48:35.952
My brother and I,
before going to school

00:48:35.952 --> 00:48:38.660
in the morning at 8
o'clock, at 6:30, 7 o'clock,

00:48:38.660 --> 00:48:39.940
we followed her to the market.

00:48:39.940 --> 00:48:41.410
There was no car at the time.

00:48:41.410 --> 00:48:44.420
Market was about a
mile, half a mile long.

00:48:44.420 --> 00:48:47.800
She walked one way, look at
the ingredient, buy on the way

00:48:47.800 --> 00:48:48.840
back.

00:48:48.840 --> 00:48:49.900
Everyone knew her.

00:48:49.900 --> 00:48:52.435
So she going to buy a case
of mushroom, which you know

00:48:52.435 --> 00:48:53.330
is dark.

00:48:53.330 --> 00:48:54.829
She know the guy's
got to sell it.

00:48:54.829 --> 00:48:55.870
He cannot give it to her.

00:48:55.870 --> 00:48:57.790
And she want to argue
the price and so forth.

00:48:57.790 --> 00:48:59.550
Get back to her
restaurant, start cooking

00:48:59.550 --> 00:49:01.460
for her lunch and dinner.

00:49:01.460 --> 00:49:03.750
Remember, there was no
refrigeration at the time.

00:49:03.750 --> 00:49:05.250
There was an icebox.

00:49:05.250 --> 00:49:07.140
So she bought a block
of ice every day

00:49:07.140 --> 00:49:08.629
to put her fish and her meat.

00:49:08.629 --> 00:49:11.170
It would have to be finished by
the day, her vegetables, too.

00:49:11.170 --> 00:49:13.560
So the day after,
everything was new again.

00:49:13.560 --> 00:49:18.000
So all the product were organic
because nothing else existed.

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:19.310
It was not a big deal.

00:49:19.310 --> 00:49:20.990
And everything was
fresh, and too,

00:49:20.990 --> 00:49:24.110
because you didn't have
refrigeration or freezer.

00:49:24.110 --> 00:49:28.040
So it was a different
type of thing,

00:49:28.040 --> 00:49:31.130
which was very menial and
very ordinary at the time,

00:49:31.130 --> 00:49:33.610
is coming back now, in
a sense-- the vengeance

00:49:33.610 --> 00:49:35.390
of something very fancy.

00:49:35.390 --> 00:49:39.160
Organic food, local food,
and stuff like this.

00:49:39.160 --> 00:49:44.630
But we come to
exaggerate in America

00:49:44.630 --> 00:49:47.286
going one end to the
other end of the spectrum.

00:49:47.286 --> 00:49:48.660
And now you have
an organic food.

00:49:48.660 --> 00:49:51.118
I've been in a restaurant where
they bring the carrot to me

00:49:51.118 --> 00:49:53.260
and said, that carrot
is called Nella.

00:49:53.260 --> 00:49:55.660
She was born on the
7th of December.

00:49:55.660 --> 00:49:56.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:49:56.980 --> 00:49:57.860
That's my carrot?

00:49:57.860 --> 00:50:01.690
So it can go a little
too far this way too.

00:50:01.690 --> 00:50:05.030
I hope we get away
from processed food.

00:50:05.030 --> 00:50:07.270
Processed food is the
worst thing you can eat.

00:50:07.270 --> 00:50:09.240
If you start looking
at what's in it,

00:50:09.240 --> 00:50:10.930
first you don't know what it is.

00:50:10.930 --> 00:50:14.380
And according to my grandmother,
you should never eat anything

00:50:14.380 --> 00:50:16.900
you cannot recognize
to start with.

00:50:16.900 --> 00:50:19.770
And on those things,
not only it becomes

00:50:19.770 --> 00:50:22.030
dangerous the kids
are eating this.

00:50:22.030 --> 00:50:25.610
And now I have seen young
kids not only recognizing

00:50:25.610 --> 00:50:28.610
the product, but recognizing
the color of the box.

00:50:28.610 --> 00:50:30.670
I want the red box, or
I want the blue box.

00:50:30.670 --> 00:50:34.130
And by the time we get away
from food, that much-- I mean,

00:50:34.130 --> 00:50:37.300
that kid should know that a
chicken's got a head and feet.

00:50:37.300 --> 00:50:40.340
It's not a square thing
with plastic on top.

00:50:40.340 --> 00:50:43.040
So we try to teach the kids,
take them to the garden,

00:50:43.040 --> 00:50:45.770
get stuff out of the ground
to make them test it,

00:50:45.770 --> 00:50:46.980
and so forth.

00:50:46.980 --> 00:50:50.030
And it's not that complicated.

00:50:50.030 --> 00:50:54.485
My granddaughter, she doesn't
like to weed the garden,

00:50:54.485 --> 00:50:57.630
but she does a great job anyway.

00:50:57.630 --> 00:51:02.190
Anyway, so I hope the future is
more than the food of the past.

00:51:02.190 --> 00:51:05.510
And it seems that it's
coming back, certainly, here

00:51:05.510 --> 00:51:06.460
at Google.

00:51:06.460 --> 00:51:08.510
I have been here before
at your restaurant.

00:51:08.510 --> 00:51:11.550
I was very impressed by
the quality of the food

00:51:11.550 --> 00:51:14.435
that you serve,
the employees too.

00:51:14.435 --> 00:51:16.060
I was even more
impressed by the price.

00:51:16.060 --> 00:51:16.935
No one paid anything.

00:51:16.935 --> 00:51:18.776
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:18.776 --> 00:51:20.747
That's amazing.

00:51:20.747 --> 00:51:21.580
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:51:21.580 --> 00:51:22.621
JACQUES PEPIN: Thank you.

00:51:25.815 --> 00:51:27.190
MARCIA GAGLIARDI:
So we are going

00:51:27.190 --> 00:51:31.010
to be looking forward to "Heart
and Soul," launching in fall

00:51:31.010 --> 00:51:35.954
of 2015, and take this wonderful
trip through your memories

00:51:35.954 --> 00:51:37.370
and all these
people in your life,

00:51:37.370 --> 00:51:38.830
and to see some of the places
that are part of your home.

00:51:38.830 --> 00:51:40.288
JACQUES PEPIN:
Thank you very much.

00:51:40.288 --> 00:51:42.770
I'm looking forward to it, too.

00:51:42.770 --> 00:51:47.490
And I hope I continue to do
some show with my granddaughter

00:51:47.490 --> 00:51:51.040
and with my daughter
and with my friend.

00:51:51.040 --> 00:51:53.430
If not, it's OK.

00:51:53.430 --> 00:51:56.760
The world of chef has
changed tremendously.

00:51:56.760 --> 00:51:59.530
And as I said, when we
get into that business,

00:51:59.530 --> 00:52:01.540
we didn't want into
that business, quote,

00:52:01.540 --> 00:52:04.260
"to become famous,"
because at that time when

00:52:04.260 --> 00:52:07.456
we work in Paris, we go
out dancing somewhere.

00:52:07.456 --> 00:52:09.580
And you invite a girl and
she says, what do you do?

00:52:09.580 --> 00:52:10.620
You say, I'm a cook.

00:52:10.620 --> 00:52:13.050
Even at the Plaza Athenee
or the great place in Paris,

00:52:13.050 --> 00:52:16.680
it was pretty low
on the social scale.

00:52:16.680 --> 00:52:19.250
Now it's very, very different.

00:52:19.250 --> 00:52:23.970
And the chefs are recognized
in many ways, maybe too much.

00:52:23.970 --> 00:52:26.680
And I know that at the French
Culinary Institute in New York

00:52:26.680 --> 00:52:29.350
or at BU, when
I'm there teaching

00:52:29.350 --> 00:52:32.610
and you have a student coming
to talk to me for an exit

00:52:32.610 --> 00:52:33.330
interview.

00:52:33.330 --> 00:52:36.350
And they say, Chef, I have a
great idea for a cooking show.

00:52:36.350 --> 00:52:38.305
I have a great
idea to do a book.

00:52:38.305 --> 00:52:40.550
They don't even know how
to peel a carrot yet.

00:52:40.550 --> 00:52:44.000
And so this is not
the right reason

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:46.630
to go into that business,
because it's very likely

00:52:46.630 --> 00:52:48.530
that it will never happen.

00:52:48.530 --> 00:52:51.080
And you still work
12 hours a day.

00:52:51.080 --> 00:52:54.880
You still get varicose veins by
the time you're 40 years old.

00:52:54.880 --> 00:52:58.430
And you sweat a lot, and you
work Saturday and Sunday.

00:52:58.430 --> 00:53:01.600
And you're not paid
that much, unless you

00:53:01.600 --> 00:53:05.360
get at the last echelon.

00:53:05.360 --> 00:53:08.470
Don't get into that business
to, quote, "become famous."

00:53:08.470 --> 00:53:10.380
But if you do it for
the right reason--

00:53:10.380 --> 00:53:11.950
that it gratifies
you, that you're

00:53:11.950 --> 00:53:15.696
happy to cook for someone, it
pleases you, makes you happy,

00:53:15.696 --> 00:53:18.070
the type of life that you want
to do-- then, well, you'll

00:53:18.070 --> 00:53:18.570
be happy.

00:53:18.570 --> 00:53:20.360
And maybe you'll
become famous, too.

00:53:20.360 --> 00:53:21.080
It may happen.

00:53:21.080 --> 00:53:24.060
But even if it doesn't,
you'll have a happy life.

00:53:24.060 --> 00:53:27.310
I mean, I've been cooking
for over 60 years.

00:53:27.310 --> 00:53:29.780
When people see me,
usually they smile.

00:53:29.780 --> 00:53:32.800
I bring pleasure to
the life of people.

00:53:32.800 --> 00:53:35.190
If I were a doctor,
they'd kind of

00:53:35.190 --> 00:53:37.310
look at me with not
too much anticipation.

00:53:40.790 --> 00:53:44.310
So it's a good life to be in if
you go in for the right reason,

00:53:44.310 --> 00:53:45.462
I think.

00:53:45.462 --> 00:53:46.920
MARCIA GAGLIARDI:
Wonderful advice.

00:53:46.920 --> 00:53:49.040
It's been such an honor
to speak with you today.

00:53:49.040 --> 00:53:49.200
JACQUES PEPIN: Thank you.

00:53:49.200 --> 00:53:49.535
Thank you very much.

00:53:49.535 --> 00:53:51.250
MARCIA GAGLIARDI: And
to hear your stories.

00:53:51.250 --> 00:53:52.583
Thank you so much for your time.

00:53:52.583 --> 00:53:54.900
[APPLAUSE]

